'''Sudo Emperor Shrine''' (崇道天皇社) is a {{ill|shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} located in {{ill|Nishikiji-chō|ja|西紀寺町|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Nara City|ja|奈良市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Nara Prefecture|ja|奈良県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Under the {{ill|Modern typeing System|ja|近代社格制度|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|1=Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it was classified as a {{ill|village shrine|ja|村社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and a {{ill|Shinzen Heihaku Shrine|ja|神饌幣帛料供進社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}<ref>Nara Prefecture History Vol. 5: Shrines, p.22</ref>. It is also referred to as "Kidera Tenno" and was historically the guardian shrine of {{ill|Renjōji Temple|ja|璉珹寺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Kidera)<ref name="kenshi">Nara Prefecture History Vol. 5: Shrines, p.267</ref>. It is located northeast of the temple and is regarded alongside {{ill|Goryō Shrine (Nara City)|ja|御霊神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Yakushidō-chō as one of the "Two Major Goryō Shrines of Nanto"<ref>Nara Prefecture History Vol. 5: Shrines, p.265</ref>.

== History ==

The shrine is traditionally said to have been established in {{ill|806|ja|806年|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Daido 1, Emperor Heijō's reign)<ref name="kenshi" /><ref name="shishi">Nara City History: Shrines and Temples Volume, p.87</ref>. According to the 1458 document "Brief Historical Records of Reianji Goryō Daimyōjin" held by the Fujii family in Gojō, the shrine was established to pacify the spirit of {{ill|Prince Sawara|ja|早良親王|qq=draft|qq=draft}}: 
<blockquote>
The deity enshrined at "Kidera Tenno" in the southern village of Nara is Sudo Emperor (Prince Sawara).
</blockquote>
It is part of the {{ill|Goryō Shrines|ja|御霊神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} dedicated to a11easing {{ill|Onryō|ja|怨霊|aa=Onryō|lt=vengeful spirits|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Goryō-e|ja|御霊会|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ceremonies were held here as one of the Eight Goryō Shrines of Nanto<ref name="heibon">Japanese Historical Place names Vol. 30: Nara Prefecture, p.520</ref>.

The {{ill|Daijōin Temple Records|ja|大乗院寺社雑事記|qq=draft|qq=draft}} entry for {{ill|1468|ja|1468th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Ōnin 2) notes that the shrine was a {{ill|branch shrine|ja|末社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of {{ill|Kasuga Shrine|ja|春日大社|1=Kasuga-taisha|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, with its Buddhist counterpart being {{ill|Maitreya|ja|弥勒菩薩|qq=draft|qq=draft}}<ref name="kenshi" /><ref name="heibon" />.

== Grounds ==

The main hall, designated as an Important Cultural Property, was originally built during the {{ill|Momoyama period|ja|桃山時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and relocated in 1623 (Genna 9) from the Kasuga Wakamiya Shrine<ref name="shishi" /><ref name="kenshi" /><ref name="heibon" />. While the hall faces south today, it faced west until 1875 (Meiji 8), when the torii gate and front gate were reoriented<ref name="shishi" />.

Auxiliary shrines on the grounds include the {{ill|Haraedo Shrine|ja|祓戸社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Tenmangū Shrine|ja|天満宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and an Inari Shrine. According to the Shrine Details Ledger (Meiji 24), these shrines were initially independent but are now combined with the Haraedo Shrine<ref name="shishi" />.

The {{ill|Kagura Hall|ja|神楽殿|qq=draft|qq=draft}} was restored in 1855 (Ansei 2), and the Ritual House was completed in 1940 (Shōwa 15)<ref name="shishi" />. The {{ill|portable shrine|ja|神輿|qq=draft|qq=draft}} storehouse houses a shrine repaired around 1717 (Kyōhō 2), which is used during the autumn festival<ref name="shishi" />.

The 1,520 square meters of shrine grounds feature large sacred trees and a seat known as the "Kasuga Viewing Stone"<ref name="shishi" />.

== Enshrined deity ==

The enshrined deity, {{ill|Prince Sawara|ja|早良親王|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, was named Crown Prince in 781 (Ten'ō 1) but was implicated in the assassination of {{ill|Fujiwara no Tanetsugu|ja|藤原種継|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and deposed in 785 (Enryaku 4)<ref name="kenshi" />. While being exiled to Awaji Province, he passed away at age 49<ref name="kenshi" />. His remains were reburied at {{ill|Yashima Mausoleum|ja|八島陵|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Yamato Province, and he was posthumously given the title "Sudo Emperor" to a11ease his spirit<ref name="kenshi" />.

