'''Sudo Emperor Shrine''' (崇道天皇社) is a [[:en:Shinto shrine|shrine]] located in {{ill|Nishikiji-chō|ja|西紀寺町|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishikiji-chō|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, [[:en:Nara (city)|Nara City]], [[:en:Nara Prefecture|Nara Prefecture]]. Under the [[:en:Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines]], it was classified as a {{ill|village shrine|ja|村社|1=Son-sha|qid=Q134917284}}{{efn|Former shrine rank|lt=Son-sha|1=modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/village shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 近代社格制度|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q712534}} and a {{ill|Shinzen Heihaku Shrine|ja|神饌幣帛料供進社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinzen Heihaku Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 近代社格制度|1=modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q712534}}<ref>Nara Prefecture History Vol. 5: Shrines, p.22</ref>. It is also referred to as "Kidera Tenno" and was historically the guardian shrine of {{ill|Renjōji Temple|ja|璉珹寺|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Renjōji Temple|qq=}} (Kidera)<ref name="kenshi">Nara Prefecture History Vol. 5: Shrines, p.267</ref>. It is located northeast of the temple and is regarded alongside {{ill|Goryō Shrine (Nara)|lt=Goryō Shrine (Nara)|lt=Goryō Shrine (Nara City)|ja|御霊神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Goryō Shrine (Nara City)|qq=}} in Yakushidō-chō as one of the "Two Major Goryō Shrines of Nanto"<ref>Nara Prefecture History Vol. 5: Shrines, p.265</ref>.

== History ==

The shrine is traditionally said to have been established in [[:en:806|806]] (Daido 1, Emperor Heijō's reign)<ref name="kenshi" /><ref name="shishi">Nara City History: Shrines and Temples Volume, p.87</ref>. According to the 1458 document "Brief Historical Records of Reianji Goryō Daimyōjin" held by the Fujii family in Gojō, the shrine was established to pacify the spirit of [[:en:Prince Sawara|Prince Sawara]]: 
<blockquote>
The deity enshrined at "Kidera Tenno" in the southern village of Nara is Sudo Emperor (Prince Sawara).
</blockquote>
It is part of the {{ill|Goryo Shrine|lt=Goryo Shrine|lt=Goryō Shrines|ja|御霊神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Goryō Shrines|qq=}} dedicated to a11easing [[:en:Onryō|vengeful spirits]], and {{ill|Goryō-e|ja|御霊会|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Goryō-e|qq=|1=goryō-e|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11489354}} ceremonies were held here as one of the Eight Goryō Shrines of Nanto<ref name="heibon">Japanese Historical Place names Vol. 30: Nara Prefecture, p.520</ref>.

The {{ill|Daijōin Temple Records|ja|大乗院寺社雑事記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daijōin Temple Records|qq=|1=Daijōin Jisha Zōjiki|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11432101}} entry for [[:en:1468|1468]] (Ōnin 2) notes that the shrine was a {{ill|branch shrine|ja|末社|lt=Massha|1=Setsumatsusha|2=ja|3=摂末社|4=zh|5=攝末社|6=es|7=Setsumatsusha|8=fr|9=Setsumatsusha|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/branch shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 摂末社}} of [[:en:Kasuga-taisha|Kasuga-taisha]], with its Buddhist counterpart being [[:en:Maitreya|Maitreya]]<ref name="kenshi" /><ref name="heibon" />.

== Grounds ==

The main hall, designated as an Important Cultural Property, was originally built during the {{ill|Momoyama period|ja|桃山時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Momoyama period|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 安土桃山時代|1=Azuchi-Momoyama period|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q319531}} and relocated in 1623 (Genna 9) from the Kasuga Wakamiya Shrine<ref name="shishi" /><ref name="kenshi" /><ref name="heibon" />. While the hall faces south today, it faced west until 1875 (Meiji 8), when the torii gate and front gate were reoriented<ref name="shishi" />.

Auxiliary shrines on the grounds include the {{ill|Haraedo Shrine|ja|祓戸社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Haraedo Shrine|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, [[:en:Tenmangū|Tenmangū Shrine]], and an Inari Shrine. According to the Shrine Details Ledger (Meiji 24), these shrines were initially independent but are now combined with the Haraedo Shrine<ref name="shishi" />.

The [[:en:Kagura-den|Kagura Hall]] was restored in 1855 (Ansei 2), and the Ritual House was completed in 1940 (Shōwa 15)<ref name="shishi" />. The [[:en:Mikoshi|Portable shrine]] storehouse houses a shrine repaired around 1717 (Kyōhō 2), which is used during the autumn festival<ref name="shishi" />.

The 1,520 square meters of shrine grounds feature large sacred trees and a seat known as the "Kasuga Viewing Stone"<ref name="shishi" />.

== Enshrined deity ==

The enshrined deity, [[:en:Prince Sawara|Prince Sawara]], was named Crown Prince in 781 (Ten'ō 1) but was implicated in the assassination of [[:en:Fujiwara no Tanetsugu|Fujiwara no Tanetsugu]] and deposed in 785 (Enryaku 4)<ref name="kenshi" />. While being exiled to Awaji Province, he passed away at age 49<ref name="kenshi" />. His remains were reburied at {{ill|Yashima Mausoleum|ja|八島陵|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yashima Mausoleum|qq=}} in Yamato Province, and he was posthumously given the title "Sudo Emperor" to a11ease his spirit<ref name="kenshi" />.

